nic.org/health/body/21459-pituitary-gland" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"text-=
brandBlue-500 underline underline-offset-[5px] decoration-1 break-words hov=
er:text-blue-800 transition">pituitary gland</a> (in your brain) and your <=
a data-identity=3D"link" href=3D"https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/body=
/22999-ovaries" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"text-brandBlue-500 underline und=
erline-offset-[5px] decoration-1 break-words hover:text-blue-800 transition=
">ovaries</a> (part of your <a data-identity=3D"link" href=3D"https://my.cl=
evelandclinic.org/health/articles/9118-female-reproductive-system" target=
=3D"_blank" class=3D"text-brandBlue-500 underline underline-offset-[5px] de=
coration-1 break-words hover:text-blue-800 transition">reproductive system<=
/a>) make and release certain hormones at certain times during your menstru=
al cycle.</p><p data-identity=3D"paragraph-element" class=3D"text-gray-800 =
my-rem16px text-rem19px leading-rem34px  ">These hormones cause the lining =
of your uterus to thicken. This happens so that if a pregnancy would occur,=
 an egg can implant into your uterine lining. Hormones also cause your ovar=
ies to release an egg (ovulation). The egg moves down your <a data-identity=
=3D"link" href=3D"https://my.clevelandclinic.org/health/body/23184-fallopia=
n-tubes" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"text-brandBlue-500 underline underline-=
offset-[5px] decoration-1 break-words hover:text-blue-800 transition">fallo=
pian tubes</a>, where it waits for sperm. If a sperm doesn=E2=80=99t fertil=
ize that egg, pregnancy doesn=E2=80=99t occur. The lining of your uterus br=
eaks down and sheds. This is your period.</p><div data-identity=3D"figure-c=
ontainer" class=3D"max-w-full inline-block my-rem32px "><figure class=3D"mr=
